2/http://www.bbc.co.uk/history/british/empire_seapower/vermeer_camera_01.shtml |archivedate=29 November 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Vanity>{{cite web|title=Reverse-Engineering a Genius (Has a Vermeer Mystery Been Solved?) |url=http://www.vanityfair.com/culture/2013/11/vermeer-secret-tool-mirrors-lenses |website=Vanity Fair |first=Kurt |last=Andersen |date=29 November 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131130173927/http://www.vanityfair.com/culture/2013/11/vermeer-secret-tool-mirrors-lenses |archivedate=30 November 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Obscura>{{cite web|title=Vermeer and the Camera Obscura |url=http://www.essentialvermeer.com/camera_obscura/co_one.html |website=Essential Vermeer 2.0 |accessdate=30 July 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140925140616/http://www.essentialvermeer.com/camera_obscura/co_three.html#.VES10MlTCSo |archivedate=25 September 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=wadum95>B. Broos, A. Blankert, J. Wadum, A. K. Wheelock Jr. (1995) ''Johannes Vermeer'', Waanders Publishers, Zwolle</ref>\n<ref name=Tims>''[[Tim's Vermeer]]'' (2013) documentary \u2013 See 40:50 onwards</ref>\n<ref name=bryson>{{cite book|last1=Bryson|first1=Bill|title=A Short History of Nearly Everything|date=2014|publisher=Lulu Press|isbn=978-1312792562|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yRuICgAAQBAJ&pg=PT442}}</ref>\n<!--\n<ref name=Dolnick>{{Cite book |name=The Forger's Spell: A True Story of Vermeer, Nazis, and the Greatest Art Hoax of the Twentieth Century |last=Dolnick |first=Edward |authorlink=Edward Dolnick |publisher=[[HarperCollins]] |year=2008 |isbn=0-06-082541-3, 9780060825416}}</ref>\n-->}}\n\n==Sources==\n* {{Cite book|title=Dutch Paintings in the Metropolitan Museum of Art|last=Liedtke|first=Walter A. |authorlink=Walter Liedtke|year=2007|publisher=[[Metropolitan Museum of Art]]|isbn=978-0-300-12028-8}}\n{{Reflist|group=Liedtke|refs=\n<ref name=p866 group=Liedtke>W. Liedtke, p. 866.</ref>\n<ref name=p867 group=Liedtke>W. Liedtke, p. 867.</ref>\n<ref name=p893 group=Liedtke>W. Liedtke, p. 893.</ref>}} \n* {{Cite book|title=Vermeer and His Milieu: A Web of Social History|last=Montias|first=John Michael|edition=reprint, illustrated|year=1991|publisher=[[Princeton University Press]]|isbn=978-0-691-00289-7}}\n{{Reflist|group=Montias|refs=\n   <ref name=p104 group=Montias>p. 104.</ref>\n   <ref name=p370 group=Montias>pp. 370\u2013371.</ref>\n   <ref name=p339 group=Montias>pp. 339\u2013344.</ref>\n}}\n* {{Cite book|title=Giants of Delft: Johannes Vermeer and the Natural Philosophers: the Parallel Search for Knowledge During the Age of Discovery|last=Huerta|first=Robert D.|year=2003|publisher=[[Bucknell University Press]]|isbn=978-0-8387-5538-9}}\n{{Reflist|group=Huerta|refs=<ref name=p42 group=Huerta>pp. 42\u201343.</ref>}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book | last=Liedtke|first=Walter |authorlink=Walter Liedtke|title= The Milkmaid by Johannes Vermeer | location=New York | publisher=The Metropolitan Museum of Art | year=2009 | isbn=9781588393449 | url=http://libmma.contentdm.oclc.org/cdm/compoundobject/collection/p15324coll10/id/121680}}\n* {{Cite book|url=http://libmma.contentdm.oclc.org/cdm/compoundobject/collection/p15324coll10/id/65202/rec/17|title=Vermeer and the Delft School|last=Liedtke|first=Walter A.|authorlink=Walter Liedtke|year=2001|publisher=[[Metropolitan Museum of Art]]|isbn=9780870999734}}\n* {{Cite book|first=Frederik H. |last=Kreuger |authorlink=Frederik H. Kreuger |year=2007 |title=New Vermeer, Life and Work of Han van Meegeren |url=http://www.quantes.nl/uitgeverij.php?aut=4 |accessdate=21 September 2009 |isbn=978-90-5959-047-2 |pages=54, 218 and 220 give examples of Van Meegeren fakes that were removed from their museum walls. Pages 220/221 give an example of a non\u2013Van Meegeren fake attributed to him |publisher=Quantes |location=Rijswijk |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100829165309/http://www.quantes.nl/uitgeverij.php?aut=4 |archivedate=29 August 2010 |df= }}\n* {{Cite book|last=Singh|first=Iona|chapter=Vermeer, Materialism and the Transcendental in Art|title=from the book, Color, Facture, Art & Design|publisher=Zero Books|location=United Kingdom|year=2012|pages=18\u201340}}\n* {{Cite book|last=Schneider|first=Nobert|year=1993|title=Vermeer|location=Cologne|publisher=Benedikt Taschen Verlag|isbn=3-8228-6377-7}}\n* {{Cite journal|last=Sheldon|first=Libby|author2=Nicola Costaros |date=February 2006|title=Johannes Vermeer's 'Young woman seated at a virginal|journal=The Burlington Magazine|issue=1235|edition=vol. CXLVIII}}\n* {{Cite book|last=Snyder|first=Laura J.|authorlink=Laura J. Snyder|year=2015|title=Eye of the Beholder: Johannes Vermeer, Antoni van Leeuwenhoek, and the Reinvention of Seeing|location=New York|publisher=[[W. W. Norton]]|isbn=978-0-393-07746-9}}\n* {{Cite book|last=Steadman|first=Philip|title=Vermeer's Camera, the truth behind the masterpieces|publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]|year=2002|isbn=0-19-280302-6|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/vermeerscameraun0000stea}}\n* {{Cite book|last=Wadum|first=J.|chapter=Contours of Vermeer|title=Vermeer Studies. Studies in the History of Art|publisher=Center for Advanced Study in the Visual Arts, Symposium Papers XXXIII|editor=I. Gaskel and M. Jonker|location=Washington/New Haven|year=1998|pages=201\u2013223}}\n* {{Cite book|first=Arthur K., Jr.|last= Wheelock|orig-year=1st. Pub. 1981|date=1988|title=Jan Vermeer|isbn=0-8109-1737-8|publisher=Abrams|location=New York}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n{{Commons}}\n{{Library resources box}}\n* [http://kalden.home.xs4all.nl/ 500 pages on Vermeer and Delft]\n* [http://www.artble.com/artists/johannes_vermeer Johannes Vermeer], biography at Artble\n* [http://www.essentialvermeer.com Essential Vermeer], website dedicated to Johannes Vermeer\n* [http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/626156/Johannes-Vermeer Johannes Vermeer] in the ''[[Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica]]''\n* [http://www.vermeerdelft.nl/ Vermeer Center Delft], center with tours about Vermeer\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Fkwl_lEJDf0&t=1s Vermeer's Mania for Maps], [[WGBH Educational Foundation|WGBH]]Forum, 30 December 2016\n* [http://colourlex.com/paintings/paintings-painter/dutch-painters/ Pigment analyses of many of Vermeer's paintings] at Colourlex\n* [https://www.rijksmuseum.nl/en/press/press-releases/the-address-of-vermeers-the-little-street-discovered Location of Vermeer's ''The Little Street'']\n\n{{Johannes Vermeer}}\n{{Art of the Dutch Golden Age}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Vermeer, Johannes}}\n[[Category:Johannes Vermeer|*]]\n[[Category:1632 births]]\n[[Category:1675 deaths]]\n[[Category:Burials at the Oude Kerk, Delft]]\n[[Category:Converts to Roman Catholicism from Calvinism]]\n[[Category:Dutch genre painters]]\n[[Category:Dutch Golden Age painters]]\n[[Category:Dutch male painters]]\n[[Category:Dutch Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:Members of the Delft Guild of Saint Luke]]\n[[Category:Artists from Delft]]\n[[Category:Dutch art collectors]]\n[[Category:Dutch art dealers]]\n", "name_user": "84.84.203.165", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200ePronunciation of name)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Johannes_Vermeer"}
{"title_page": "Neoclytus acteon", "text_new": "{{short description|Species of beetle}}\n{{italic title}}\n{{Taxobox\n| regnum = [[Animal]]ia\n| phylum = [[Arthropod]]a\n| classis = [[Insect]]a\n| ordo = [[Beetle|Coleoptera]]\n| subordo = [[Polyphaga]]\n| familia = [[Cerambycidae]]\n| genus = ''[[Neoclytus]]''\n| species = '''''N. acteon'''''\n| binomial = ''Neoclytus acteon''\n| binomial_authority = (Chevrolat, 1860)\n| synonyms = \n}}\n\n'''''Neoclytus acteon''''' is a species of [[beetle]] in the family [[Cerambycidae]]. It was described by Chevrolat in 1860.<ref>Bezark, Larry G. [http://plant.cdfa.ca.gov/byciddb/bycidview.asp A Photographic Catalog of the Cerambycidae of the World]. Retrieved on 22 May 2012.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q14706417}}\n\n[[Category:Neoclytus|acteon]]\n[[Category:Beetles described in 1860]]\n\n\n{{clytini-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Species of beetle}}\n{{italic title}}\n{{Taxobox\n| regnum = [[Animal]]ia\n| phylum = [[Arthropod]]a\n| classis = [[Insect]]a\n| ordo = [[Beetle|Coleoptera]]\n| subordo = [[Polyphaga]]\n| familia = [[Cerambycidae]]\n| genus = '''''[[Neoclytus]]'''''\n| species = '''''N. acteon'''''\n| binomial = ''Neoclytus acteon''\n| binomial_authority = (Chevrolat, 1860)\n| synonyms = \n}}\n\n'''''Neoclytus acteon''''' is a species of [[beetle]] in the family [[Cerambycidae]]. It was described by Chevrolat in 1860.<ref>Bezark, Larry G. [http://plant.cdfa.ca.gov/byciddb/bycidview.asp A Photographic Catalog of the Cerambycidae of the World]. Retrieved on 22 May 2012.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q14706417}}\n\n[[Category:Neoclytus]]\n[[Category:Beetles described in 1860]]\n\n\n{{clytini-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Polinizador", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neoclytus_acteon"}
{"title_page": "Serena DeBeer", "text_new": "{{Infobox scientist\n| honorific_prefix = Prof. Dr.\n| name = Serena DeBeer <!-- use common name/article title -->\n| honorific_suffix = |\n| caption = \n| birth_date = {{Birth year|1973}} <!-- {{Birth date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} for living people supply only the year with {{Birth year and age|YYYY}} unless the exact date is already widely published, as per [[WP:DOB]]. For people who have died, use {{Birth date|YYYY|MM|DD}}. -->\n| nationality = American\n| fields = [[Chemistry]]<br>\n| education = ''Chemistry'' Southwestern University, TX <br> ''PhD'' Stanford University (2002)<br>\n| known_for = [[X-ray spectroscopy]]<br> [[nitrogenase]]<br>[[photosystem II]]<br>  [[hydrogenase]]<br> [[Methane monooxygenase]]\n| workplaces = [[Stanford Synchrotron Radiation Lightsource|SSRL]] [[SLAC]] [[Stanford University]] (2001\u20132009)<br> [[Cornell University]] (2009-present)<br> [[Ruhr University Bochum]] (2014\u2013present)<br>\n[[Max Planck Institute for Chemical Energy Conversion]] (2011\u2013present)\n| other_names = Serena DeBeer George\n| doctoral_advisor = [[Edward I. Solomon]]<br>\n[[Keith O. Hodgson]]\n| image = DeBeer Quer 1080P 2.jpg\n}}\n\n'''Serena DeBeer''' (born 1973) is an American chemist. She is currently a W3-Professor and the director at the [[Max Planck Institute for Chemical Energy Conversion]] in [[M\u00fclheim|Muelheim an der Ruhr]], [[Germany]], where she heads the Department of Inorganic Spectroscopy. Her expertise lies in the application and development of [[X-ray spectroscopy|X-ray based spectroscopic]] methods as probes of [[electronic structure]] in biological and chemical [[catalysis]].\n\n== Education and career ==\nSerena DeBeer studied at [[Southwestern University]], [[Georgetown, Texas|Georgetown]], TX (USA) where she completed her [[Bachelor's degree|bachelor]] program in [[Chemistry]], with minor in [[Mathematics]] in 1995 (with honors). She received her doctorate from [[Stanford University]] in 2002, working under the guidance of [[Edward I. Solomon]] and [[Keith Hodgson|Keith O. Hodgson]]. She then moved to [[SLAC National Accelerator Laboratory]], where she worked first as a beamline scientist (2001-2003) at the [[Stanford Synchrotron Radiation Lightsource|Stanford Synchrotron Radiation Laboratory]], and later as staff scientist (2003-2009). In the Fall of 2009, she relocated to [[Cornell University]] in [[Ithaca, New York|Ithaca, NY]] (USA), where she accepted a faculty position as [[Assistant professor|Assistant Professor]] at the Department of Chemistry and Chemical Biology.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://chemistry.cornell.edu/serena-debeer |title = Serena DeBeer &#124; Chemistry & Chemical Biology Cornell Arts & Sciences}}</ref> In the Summer of 2011, she moved to Germany and started to work as a W2-Professor and research group leader at the Max Planck Institute for Bioinorganic Chemistry (since 2012 [[Max Planck Institute for Chemical Energy Conversion|Max Planck Institute for Chemical Energy Conversion, MPI CEC]]) in [[M\u00fclheim|M\u00fclheim an der Ruhr]], Germany. Since 2012 she has held the position of an Adjunct Professor at [[Cornell University]] as well as an Honorary Faculty position at [[Ruhr University Bochum]] since 2014.<ref name=\"rub\">{{Cite web|url=https://news.rub.de/leute/2017-03-13-max-planck-institut-honorarprofessorin-der-rub-ist-neue-direktorin|title=Honorarprofessorin der RUB ist neue Direktorin|website=news.rub.de|language=de|access-date=2019-08-08}}</ref> DeBeer headed the research group \"X-ray Spectroscopy\" at MPI CEC until 2017 when she was appointed director at this institute and promoted to a W3-Professor. Currently she leads the department of \"Inorganic Spectroscopy\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cec.mpg.de/1/research/1087/prof-dr-serena-debeer/|title=Prof. Dr. Serena DeBeer|website=cec.mpg.de|access-date=2019-12-02}}</ref> at MPI CEC. Additionally, she is the group leader of the PINK beamline<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.helmholtz-berlin.de/projects/emil/instruments/analytics/pink_en.html|title=PINK|last=Energie|first=Helmholtz-Zentrum Berlin f\u00fcr Materialien und|website=HZB Website|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-12-02}}</ref> project at the Energy and Materials In-Situ Laboratory<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.helmholtz-berlin.de/forschung/quellen/corelabs/emil/index_en.html|title=Energy Materials In-Situ Laboratory Berlin|last=Energie|first=Helmholtz-Zentrum Berlin f\u00fcr Materialien und|website=HZB Website|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-12-02}}</ref> at the [[Helmholtz-Zentrum Berlin|Helmholtz Zentrum Berlin]], Germany.\n\n== Research ==\nResearch in the DeBeer group focuses on answering \u00a0fundamental questions in energy research. Namely, how does one reversibly store and release energy from chemical bonds using earth abundant transition metals? And how is this done most efficiently? Her research group studies homogeneous, heterogeneous and biological catalysts in order to answer these questions, with a primary focus on enzymatic catalysis. She is an expert in the application of advanced X-ray spectroscopy to understand catalytic transformations.\n\n===Nitrogenase===\nA strong focus of her research is to study the enzyme that is responsible for the conversion of [[Nitrogen|dinitrogen]] (N<sub>2</sub>) to [[ammonia]] (NH<sub>3</sub>)\u2014[[Nitrogenase]]. Serena DeBeer and her group study this remarkable system comprising a [[FeMoco|FeMo cofactor]] (FeMoco) as its active site, and structural model complexes utilizing high-resolution [[X-ray absorption spectroscopy|X-ray absorption]] (XAS) and [[X-ray emission spectroscopy]] (XES). Through this work, great progress has been made in understanding the structure of this active site. A key contribution was a spectroscopic identification of the central atom in the active site as a carbide.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Lancaster|first=K. M.|last2=Roemelt|first2=M.|last3=Ettenhuber|first3=P.|last4=Hu|first4=Y.|last5=Ribbe|first5=M. W.|last6=Neese|first6=F.|last7=Bergmann|first7=U.|last8=DeBeer|first8=S.|date=2011-11-18|title=X-ray Emission Spectroscopy Evidences a Central Carbon in the Nitrogenase Iron-Molybdenum Cofactor|journal=Science|language=en|volume=334|issue=6058|pages=974\u2013977|doi=10.1126/science.1206445|issn=0036-8075|pmc=3800678|pmid=22096198|bibcode=2011Sci...334..974L}}</ref> Moreover, the application of high-resolution XAS spectroscopy supported with theoretical calculations, allowed her group to succeed in the assignment of the oxidation state of the Mo atom in the FeMoco as Mo(III).<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bjornsson|first=Ragnar|last2=Lima|first2=Frederico A.|last3=Spatzal|first3=Thomas|last4=Weyherm\u00fcller|first4=Thomas|last5=Glatzel|first5=Pieter|last6=Bill|first6=Eckhard|last7=Einsle|first7=Oliver|last8=Neese|first8=Frank|last9=DeBeer|first9=Serena|date=2014|title=Identification of a spin-coupled Mo(III) in the nitrogenase iron\u2013molybdenum cofactor|journal=Chem. Sci.|language=en|volume=5|issue=8|pages=3096\u20133103|doi=10.1039/C4SC00337C|issn=2041-6520}}</ref> This study was followed up later with the experimental evidence of a non-Hund spin configuration at the Mo atom by means of [[X-ray magnetic circular dichroism|X-ray Magnetic Circular Dichroism]] (XMCD) spectroscopy.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=Kowalska|first=Joanna K.|last2=Henthorn|first2=Justin T.|last3=Van Stappen|first3=Casey|last4=Trncik|first4=Christian|last5=Einsle|first5=Oliver|last6=Keavney|first6=David|last7=DeBeer|first7=Serena|date=2019-07-08|title=X-ray Magnetic Circular Dichroism Spectroscopy Applied to Nitrogenase and Related Models: Experimental Evidence for a Spin-Coupled Molybdenum(III) Center|journal=Angewandte Chemie International Edition|language=en|volume=58|issue=28|pages=9373\u20139377|doi=10.1002/anie.201901899|pmc=6772009|pmid=31119827}}</ref> Another approach in this field concerns comparative studies of different forms of nitrogenase enzymes with FeMoco and FeVco active sites,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Rees|first=Julian A.|last2=Bjornsson|first2=Ragnar|last3=Kowalska|first3=Joanna K.|last4=Lima|first4=Frederico A.|last5=Schlesier|first5=Julia|last6=Sippel|first6=Daniel|last7=Weyherm\u00fcller|first7=Thomas|last8=Einsle|first8=Oliver|last9=Kovacs|first9=Julie A. |authorlink9=Julie Kovacs|last10=DeBeer|first10=Serena|date=2017|title=Comparative electronic structures of nitrogenase FeMoco and FeVco|journal=Dalton Transactions|language=en|volume=46|issue=8|pages=2445\u20132455|doi=10.1039/C7DT00128B|issn=1477-9226|pmc=5322470|pmid=28154874}}</ref> [[Selenium]]-incorporated FeMoco,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Henthorn|first=Justin T.|last2=Arias|first2=Renee J.|last3=Koroidov|first3=Sergey|last4=Kroll|first4=Thomas|last5=Sokaras|first5=Dimosthenis|last6=Bergmann|first6=Uwe|last7=Rees|first7=Douglas C.|last8=DeBeer|first8=Serena|date=2019-08-28|title=Localized Electronic Structure of Nitrogenase FeMoco Revealed by Selenium K-Edge High Resolution X-ray Absorption Spectroscopy|journal=Journal of the American Chemical Society|language=en|volume=141|issue=34|pages=13676\u201313688|doi=10.1021/jacs.9b06988|issn=0002-7863|pmc=6716209|pmid=31356071}}</ref> as well as spectroscopic characterization of the first intermediate state of the nitrogenase catalytic cycle (E<sub>1</sub>).<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Van Stappen|first=Casey|last2=Thorhallsson|first2=Albert Thor|last3=Decamps|first3=Laure|last4=Bjornsson|first4=Ragnar|last5=DeBeer|first5=Serena|date=2019|title=Resolving the structure of the E 1 state of Mo nitrogenase through Mo and Fe K-edge EXAFS and QM/MM calculations|journal=Chemical Science|language=en|volume=10|issue=42|pages=9807\u20139821|doi=10.1039/C9SC02187F|issn=2041-6520}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Van Stappen|first=Casey|last2=Davydov|first2=Roman|last3=Yang|first3=Zhi-Yong|last4=Fan|first4=Ruixi|last5=Guo|first5=Yisong|last6=Bill|first6=Eckhard|last7=Seefeldt|first7=Lance C.|last8=Hoffman|first8=Brian M.|last9=DeBeer|first9=Serena|date=2019-09-16|title=Spectroscopic Description of the E 1 State of Mo Nitrogenase Based on Mo and Fe X-ray Absorption and M\u00f6ssbauer Studies|journal=Inorganic Chemistry|language=en|volume=58|issue=18|pages=12365\u201312376|doi=10.1021/acs.inorgchem.9b01951|issn=0020-1669|pmc=6751781|pmid=31441651}}</ref>\n\n=== Methane monooxygenase ===\nAnother important chemical conversion studied by her group is the catalytic oxidation of [[methane]] to [[methanol]]. Nature utilizes a group of enzymes called [[methane monooxygenase]] (MMOs). The active site of this enzyme that enables the cleavage of the C-H of [[methane]] is a dinuclear Fe(IV) intermediate Q found in the hydroxylase protein (MMOH) of MMO. Spectroscopic studies in the DeBeer group have provided new insights into the structure of this diiron complex. Through applications of advanced X-ray spectroscopic studies like high-resolution [[X-ray absorption spectroscopy|XAS]] they characterized the key intermediate in biological methane oxidation as an open-core diiron structure (with Fe<sup>IV</sup>=O motif).<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Castillo|first=Rebeca G.|last2=Banerjee|first2=Rahul|last3=Allpress|first3=Caleb J.|last4=Rohde|first4=Gregory T.|last5=Bill|first5=Eckhard|last6=Que|first6=Lawrence|last7=Lipscomb|first7=John D.|last8=DeBeer|first8=Serena|date=2017-12-13|title=High-Energy-Resolution Fluorescence-Detected X-ray Absorption of the Q Intermediate of Soluble Methane Monooxygenase|journal=Journal of the American Chemical Society|language=en|volume=139|issue=49|pages=18024\u201318033|doi=10.1021/jacs.7b09560|pmid=29136468|pmc=5729100|issn=0002-7863}}</ref> Additional [[Extended X-ray absorption fine structure|EXAFS]] studies confirmed this finding by showing no evidence for a short Fe-Fe distance but rather a long diiron distance consistent with an open-core structure.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Cutsail|first=George E.|last2=Banerjee|first2=Rahul|last3=Zhou|first3=Ang|last4=Que|first4=Lawrence|last5=Lipscomb|first5=John D.|last6=DeBeer|first6=Serena|date=2018-12-05|title=High-Resolution Extended X-ray Absorption Fine Structure Analysis Provides Evidence for a Longer Fe\u00b7\u00b7\u00b7Fe Distance in the Q Intermediate of Methane Monooxygenase|journal=Journal of the American Chemical Society|language=en|volume=140|issue=48|pages=16807\u201316820|doi=10.1021/jacs.8b10313|pmid=30398343|pmc=6470014|issn=0002-7863}}</ref>\n\n=== Spectroscopy Development ===\nRecent work of DeBeer's group has focused on developing the full information content of various X-ray spectroscopic methods and their application to biological catalysts.\n\nAmong these methods are:\n\n==== Valence X-ray Emission Spectroscopy  ====\nIn this method (also known as VtC XES = Valence-to-Core X-ray Emission Spectroscopy), one monitors the resultant fluorescence after a valence electron refills the ionized metal 1s core hole. As such, valence XES spectra provide a map of ligand ionization energies, and provides information on both ligand identity and protonation state. A prominent application of this method its use to identify the central carbon atom in FeMo cofactor of Nitrogenase  (see section [[Serena DeBeer#Nitrogenase|Nitrogenase]]).<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==== Resonant valence XES (RXES) or Resonant Inelastic X-ray Scattering (RIXS) ====\nThe DeBeer group is actively involved in the development and application of RXES/[[Resonant inelastic X-ray scattering|RIXS]] based methods in both the hard and soft [[X-ray]] regime. These include 1s-Valence [[Resonant inelastic X-ray scattering|RIXS]] as a means to obtain ligand-selective [[X-ray absorption spectroscopy|XAS]]<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Hall|first=Eleanor R.|last2=Pollock|first2=Christopher J.|last3=Bendix|first3=Jesper|last4=Collins|first4=Terrence J.|last5=Glatzel|first5=Pieter|last6=DeBeer|first6=Serena|date=2014-07-16|title=Valence-to-Core-Detected X-ray Absorption Spectroscopy: Targeting Ligand Selectivity|journal=Journal of the American Chemical Society|language=en|volume=136|issue=28|pages=10076\u201310084|doi=10.1021/ja504206y|pmid=24946007|issn=0002-7863}}</ref> and 2p3d [[Resonant inelastic X-ray scattering|RIXS]] as a means to map out the d-d excitations.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Van Kuiken|first=Benjamin E.|last2=Hahn|first2=Anselm W.|last3=Nayyar|first3=Brahamjot|last4=Schiewer|first4=Christine E.|last5=Lee|first5=Sonny C.|last6=Meyer|first6=Franc|last7=Weyherm\u00fcller|first7=Thomas|last8=Nicolaou|first8=Alessandro|last9=Cui|first9=Yi-Tao|last10=Miyawaki|first10=Jun|last11=Harada|first11=Yoshihisa|date=2018-06-18|title=Electronic Spectra of Iron\u2013Sulfur Complexes Measured by 2p3d RIXS Spectroscopy|journal=Inorganic Chemistry|language=en|volume=57|issue=12|pages=7355\u20137361|doi=10.1021/acs.inorgchem.8b01010|pmid=29847108|issn=0020-1669}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Hahn|first=Anselm W.|last2=Van Kuiken|first2=Benjamin E.|last3=al Samarai|first3=Mustafa|last4=Atanasov|first4=Mihail|last5=Weyherm\u00fcller|first5=Thomas|last6=Cui|first6=Yi-Tao|last7=Miyawaki|first7=Jun|last8=Harada|first8=Yoshihisa|last9=Nicolaou|first9=Alessandro|last10=DeBeer|first10=Serena|date=2017-07-17|title=Measurement of the Ligand Field Spectra of Ferrous and Ferric Iron Chlorides Using 2p3d RIXS|journal=Inorganic Chemistry|language=en|volume=56|issue=14|pages=8203\u20138211|doi=10.1021/acs.inorgchem.7b00940|pmid=28653856|issn=0020-1669}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Hahn|first=Anselm W.|last2=Van Kuiken|first2=Benjamin E.|last3=Chilkuri|first3=Vijay Gopal|last4=Levin|first4=Natalia|last5=Bill|first5=Eckhard|last6=Weyherm\u00fcller|first6=Thomas|last7=Nicolaou|first7=Alessandro|last8=Miyawaki|first8=Jun|last9=Harada|first9=Yoshihisa|last10=DeBeer|first10=Serena|date=2018-08-06|title=Probing the Valence Electronic Structure of Low-Spin Ferrous and Ferric Complexes Using 2p3d Resonant Inelastic X-ray Scattering (RIXS)|journal=Inorganic Chemistry|language=en|volume=57|issue=15|pages=9515\u20139530|doi=10.1021/acs.inorgchem.8b01550|pmid=30044087|issn=0020-1669}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Van Kuiken|first=Benjamin E.|last2=Hahn|first2=Anselm W.|last3=Maganas|first3=Dimitrios|last4=DeBeer|first4=Serena|date=2016-11-07|title=Measuring Spin-Allowed and Spin-Forbidden d\u2013d Excitations in Vanadium Complexes with 2p3d Resonant Inelastic X-ray Scattering|journal=Inorganic Chemistry|language=en|volume=55|issue=21|pages=11497\u201311501|doi=10.1021/acs.inorgchem.6b02053|pmid=27731986|issn=0020-1669}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Maganas|first=Dimitrios|last2=DeBeer|first2=Serena|last3=Neese|first3=Frank|date=2017-10-02|title=A Restricted Open Configuration Interaction with Singles Method To Calculate Valence-to-Core Resonant X-ray Emission Spectra: A Case Study|journal=Inorganic Chemistry|language=en|volume=56|issue=19|pages=11819\u201311836|doi=10.1021/acs.inorgchem.7b01810|issn=0020-1669|pmc=5692824|pmid=28920680}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Al Samarai|first=Mustafa|last2=Hahn|first2=Anselm W.|last3=Beheshti Askari|first3=Abbas|last4=Cui|first4=Yi-Tao|last5=Yamazoe|first5=Kosuke|last6=Miyawaki|first6=Jun|last7=Harada|first7=Yoshihisa|last8=R\u00fcdiger|first8=Olaf|last9=DeBeer|first9=Serena|date=2019-10-23|title=Elucidation of Structure\u2013Activity Correlations in a Nickel Manganese Oxide Oxygen Evolution Reaction Catalyst by Operando Ni L-Edge X-ray Absorption Spectroscopy and 2p3d Resonant Inelastic X-ray Scattering|journal=ACS Applied Materials & Interfaces|language=en|volume=11|issue=42|pages=38595\u201338605|doi=10.1021/acsami.9b06752|pmid=31523947|issn=1944-8244}}</ref>\n\n==== X-ray Magnetic Circular Dichroism (XMCD) ====\nThis method has been extensively used in solid-state materials, to determine the magnetic properties. Past applications to (bio-)inorganic or protein systems were lacking proper qualitative and quantitative interpretations. DeBeer's group expanded the information that can be obtained from XMCD of covalent systems.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kowalska|first=Joanna K.|last2=Nayyar|first2=Brahamjot|last3=Rees|first3=Julian A.|last4=Schiewer|first4=Christine E.|last5=Lee|first5=Sonny C.|last6=Kovacs|first6=Julie A.|last7=Meyer|first7=Franc|last8=Weyherm\u00fcller|first8=Thomas|last9=Otero|first9=Edwige|last10=DeBeer|first10=Serena|date=2017-07-17|title=Iron L 2,3 -Edge X-ray Absorption and X-ray Magnetic Circular Dichroism Studies of Molecular Iron Complexes with Relevance to the FeMoco and FeVco Active Sites of Nitrogenase|journal=Inorganic Chemistry|language=en|volume=56|issue=14|pages=8147\u20138158|doi=10.1021/acs.inorgchem.7b00852|issn=0020-1669|pmc=5516708|pmid=28653855}}</ref> To date, this been the only one method able to provide evidence for the proposed non-Hund configuration at the Mo atom in Nitrogenase<ref name=\":1\" /> (see section [[Serena DeBeer#Nitrogenase|Nitrogeanse]]).\n\n=== Instrumentation ===\n\n==== A laboratory based dispersive X-ray Emission Spectrometer ====\nThe group of Serena DeBeer in collaboration with the group of Prof. Birgit Kangie\u00dfer at [[Technical University of Berlin|TU Berlin]], developed an in-house dispersive X-ray Emission Spectroscopy (XES) setup. The setup that utilizes a laboratory X\u2011ray source (Metal Jet) in combination with a von Hamos full cylinder optic with Highly Annealed Pyrolytic Graphite (HAPG) crystal and a CCD detector. This allows obtaining spectra in the 2.4-9 keV range. Moreover, this spectrometer is an alternative to synchrotron-based beamlines for concentrated samples.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Malzer|first=Wolfgang|last2=Gr\u00f6tzsch|first2=Daniel|last3=Gnewkow|first3=Richard|last4=Schlesiger|first4=Christopher|last5=Kowalewski|first5=Fabian|last6=Van Kuiken|first6=Benjamin|last7=DeBeer|first7=Serena|last8=Kanngie\u00dfer|first8=Birgit|date=November 2018|title=A laboratory spectrometer for high throughput X-ray emission spectroscopy in catalysis research|journal=Review of Scientific Instruments|language=en|volume=89|issue=11|pages=113111|doi=10.1063/1.5035171|pmid=30501328|issn=0034-6748|bibcode=2018RScI...89k3111M}}</ref>\n\n==== PINK Beamline ====\nThe DeBeer group is also leading the development of the PINK beamline<ref name=\":2\" /> at the Energy Materials In-situ Laboratory<ref name=\":3\" /> at the [[Helmholtz-Zentrum Berlin|Helmholtz Zentrum Berlin]]. Dr. Sergey Peredkov is the lead designer and instrument scientist for this project. This beamline operates in 2-10 keV energy regime, either in a \u201cpink\u201d beam mode with multilayer mirror or with monochromatic beam (by addition of a double crystal [[monochromator]]). The beamline is presently in a commissioning phase.\n\n== Awards and recognition ==\n\n* [[European Research Council]] (ERC) Synergy Grant for the project: Unravelling the secrets of Cu-based catalysts for C-H activation (CUBE). Collaborative project with researchers from [[University of Oslo]] (Norway), [[Norwegian University of Life Sciences]] (Norway) and [[University of Turin]] (Italy) (2019) <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cec.mpg.de/en/news/detail-view/news/erc-synergy-grant-for-serena-debeer-and-an-international-and-interdisciplinary-team/|title=ERC Synergy Grant for Serena DeBeer and an international and interdisciplinary team|website=cec.mpg.de|access-date=2019-11-27}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://erc.europa.eu/news-events/magazine/erc-2019-synergy-grants-examples|title=ERC 2019 Synergy Grants examples|date=2019-10-10|website=ERC: European Research Council|language=en|access-date=2019-11-27}}</ref>\n* Associate Editor for [[Chemical Science (journal)|Chemical Science]] (2018\u2013present)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blogs.rsc.org/sc/2018/12/11/serena-debeer-joins-chemical-science/|title=Serena DeBeer joins Chemical Science as an Associate Editor \u2013 Chemical Science Blog|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-27}}</ref>\n* Inorganic Chemistry Lectureship Award (2016) <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://communities.acs.org/groups/wcc-newsletter/blog/2017/06/06/dr-serena-debeer-2016-inorganic-chemistry-lecturship-award|title=Dr. Serena Debeer - 2016 Inorganic Chemistry Le... {{!}} ACS Network|website=communities.acs.org|access-date=2019-11-27}}</ref>\n* [[Society of Biological Inorganic Chemistry]] (SBIC), Early Career Award (2015)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://sbichem.org/SBIC-News/2015-SBIC-Early-Career-Award-Winner-Serena-DeBeer.aspx|title=Serena DeBeer SBIC Early Career Award|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n* [[European Research Council|European Research Counc]][[European Research Council|il]] (ERC) Consolidator grant for the project: Spectroscopic Studies of N<sub>2</sub> Reduction: From Biological to Heterogeneous Catalysis (N2ase) (2013)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cordis.europa.eu/project/rcn/191266/factsheet/it|title=ERC Consolidator Grant: N2ase|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n* Kavli Fellow, [[National Academy of Sciences|U.S. National Academy of Sciences]] (2012)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nasonline.org/programs/kavli-frontiers-of-science/frontiers-alumni/alumni-directory/serena-debeer.html|title=Serena DeBeer|website=www.nasonline.org|access-date=2019-11-27}}</ref>\n* [[Sloan Research Fellowship|Alfred P. Sloan Research Fellow]] (2011-2013)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sloan.org/past-fellows|title=Past Fellows|website=sloan.org|access-date=2019-11-27}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://cec.mpg.de/1/research/1087/prof-dr-serena-debeer/ Prof. Dr. Ser][https://cec.mpg.de/1/research/1087/prof-dr-serena-debeer/ ena DeBeer]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:DeBeer, Serena}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American women chemists]]\n[[Category:Stanford University alumni]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women scientists]]\n[[Category:Cornell University faculty]]\n[[Category:1973 births]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox scientist\n| honorific_prefix = Prof. Dr.\n| name = Serena DeBeer <!-- use common name/article title -->\n| honorific_suffix = |\n| caption = \n| birth_date = {{Birth year|1973}} <!-- {{Birth date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} for living people supply only the year with {{Birth year and age|YYYY}} unless the exact date is already widely published, as per [[WP:DOB]]. For people who have died, use {{Birth date|YYYY|MM|DD}}. -->\n| nationality = American\n| fields = [[Chemistry]]<br>\n| education = ''Chemistry'' Southwestern University, TX <br> ''PhD'' Stanford University (2002)<br>\n| known_for = [[X-ray spectroscopy]]<br> [[nitrogenase]]<br>[[photosystem II]]<br>  [[hydrogenase]]<br> [[Methane monooxygenase]]\n| workplaces = [[Stanford Synchrotron Radiation Lightsource|SSRL]] [[SLAC]] [[Stanford University]] (2001\u20132009)<br> [[Cornell University]] (2009-present)<br> [[Ruhr University Bochum]] (2014\u2013present)<br>\n[[Max Planck Institute for Chemical Energy Conversion]] (2011\u2013present)\n| other_names = Serena DeBeer George\n| doctoral_advisor = [[Edward I. Solomon]]<br>\n[[Keith O. Hodgson]]\n| image = DeBeer Quer 1080P 2.jpg\n}}\n\n'''Serena DeBeer''' (born 1973) is an American chemist. She is currently a W3-Professor and the director at the [[Max Planck Institute for Chemical Energy Conversion]] in [[M\u00fclheim|Muelheim an der Ruhr]], [[Germany]], where she heads the Department of Inorganic Spectroscopy. Her expertise lies in the application and development of [[X-ray spectroscopy|X-ray based spectroscopic]] methods as probes of [[electronic structure]] in biological and chemical [[catalysis]].\n\n== Education and career ==\nSerena DeBeer studied at [[Southwestern University]], [[Georgetown, Texas|Georgetown]], TX (USA) where she completed her [[Bachelor's degree|bachelor]] program in Chemistry, with minor in [[Mathematics]] in 1995 (with honors). She received her doctorate from [[Stanford University]] in 2002, working under the guidance of [[Edward I. Solomon]] and [[Keith Hodgson|Keith O. Hodgson]]. She then moved to [[SLAC National Accelerator Laboratory]], where she worked first as a beamline scientist (2001-2003) at the [[Stanford Synchrotron Radiation Lightsource|Stanford Synchrotron Radiation Laboratory]], and later as staff scientist (2003-2009). In the Fall of 2009, she relocated to [[Cornell University]] in [[Ithaca, New York|Ithaca, NY]] (USA), where she accepted a faculty position as [[Assistant professor|Assistant Professor]] at the Department of Chemistry and Chemical Biology.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://chemistry.cornell.edu/serena-debeer |title = Serena DeBeer &#124; Chemistry & Chemical Biology Cornell Arts & Sciences}}</ref> In the Summer of 2011, she moved to Germany and started to work as a W2-Professor and research group leader at the Max Planck Institute for Bioinorganic Chemistry (since 2012 [[Max Planck Institute for Chemical Energy Conversion|Max Planck Institute for Chemical Energy Conversion, MPI CEC]]) in [[M\u00fclheim|M\u00fclheim an der Ruhr]], Germany. Since 2012 she has held the position of an Adjunct Professor at [[Cornell University]] as well as an Honorary Faculty position at [[Ruhr University Bochum]] since 2014.<ref name=\"rub\">{{Cite web|url=https://news.rub.de/leute/2017-03-13-max-planck-institut-honorarprofessorin-der-rub-ist-neue-direktorin|title=Honorarprofessorin der RUB ist neue Direktorin|website=news.rub.de|language=de|access-date=2019-08-08}}</ref> DeBeer headed the research group \"X-ray Spectroscopy\" at MPI CEC until 2017 when she was appointed director at this institute and promoted to a W3-Professor. Currently she leads the department of \"Inorganic Spectroscopy\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cec.mpg.de/1/research/1087/prof-dr-serena-debeer/|title=Prof. Dr. Serena DeBeer|website=cec.mpg.de|access-date=2019-12-02}}</ref> at MPI CEC. Additionally, she is the group leader of the PINK beamline<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.helmholtz-berlin.de/projects/emil/instruments/analytics/pink_en.html|title=PINK|last=Energie|first=Helmholtz-Zentrum Berlin f\u00fcr Materialien und|website=HZB Website|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-12-02}}</ref> project at the Energy and Materials In-Situ Laboratory<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.helmholtz-berlin.de/forschung/quellen/corelabs/emil/index_en.html|title=Energy Materials In-Situ Laboratory Berlin|last=Energie|first=Helmholtz-Zentrum Berlin f\u00fcr Materialien und|website=HZB Website|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-12-02}}</ref> at the [[Helmholtz-Zentrum Berlin|Helmholtz Zentrum Berlin]], Germany.\n\n== Research ==\nResearch in the DeBeer group focuses on answering \u00a0fundamental questions in energy research. Namely, how does one reversibly store and release energy from chemical bonds using earth abundant transition metals? And how is this done most efficiently? Her research group studies homogeneous, heterogeneous and biological catalysts in order to answer these questions, with a primary focus on enzymatic catalysis. She is an expert in the application of advanced X-ray spectroscopy to understand catalytic transformations.\n\n===Nitrogenase===\nA strong focus of her research is to study the enzyme that is responsible for the conversion of [[Nitrogen|dinitrogen]] (N<sub>2</sub>) to [[ammonia]] (NH<sub>3</sub>)\u2014[[Nitrogenase]]. Serena DeBeer and her group study this remarkable system comprising a [[FeMoco|FeMo cofactor]] (FeMoco) as its active site, and structural model complexes utilizing high-resolution [[X-ray absorption spectroscopy|X-ray absorption]] (XAS) and [[X-ray emission spectroscopy]] (XES). Through this work, great progress has been made in understanding the structure of this active site. A key contribution was a spectroscopic identification of the central atom in the active site as a carbide.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Lancaster|first=K. M.|last2=Roemelt|first2=M.|last3=Ettenhuber|first3=P.|last4=Hu|first4=Y.|last5=Ribbe|first5=M. W.|last6=Neese|first6=F.|last7=Bergmann|first7=U.|last8=DeBeer|first8=S.|date=2011-11-18|title=X-ray Emission Spectroscopy Evidences a Central Carbon in the Nitrogenase Iron-Molybdenum Cofactor|journal=Science|language=en|volume=334|issue=6058|pages=974\u2013977|doi=10.1126/science.1206445|issn=0036-8075|pmc=3800678|pmid=22096198|bibcode=2011Sci...334..974L}}</ref> Moreover, the application of high-resolution XAS spectroscopy supported with theoretical calculations, allowed her group to succeed in the assignment of the oxidation state of the Mo atom in the FeMoco as Mo(III).<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bjornsson|first=Ragnar|last2=Lima|first2=Frederico A.|last3=Spatzal|first3=Thomas|last4=Weyherm\u00fcller|first4=Thomas|last5=Glatzel|first5=Pieter|last6=Bill|first6=Eckhard|last7=Einsle|first7=Oliver|last8=Neese|first8=Frank|last9=DeBeer|first9=Serena|date=2014|title=Identification of a spin-coupled Mo(III) in the nitrogenase iron\u2013molybdenum cofactor|journal=Chem. Sci.|language=en|volume=5|issue=8|pages=3096\u20133103|doi=10.1039/C4SC00337C|issn=2041-6520}}</ref> This study was followed up later with the experimental evidence of a non-Hund spin configuration at the Mo atom by means of [[X-ray magnetic circular dichroism|X-ray Magnetic Circular Dichroism]] (XMCD) spectroscopy.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=Kowalska|first=Joanna K.|last2=Henthorn|first2=Justin T.|last3=Van Stappen|first3=Casey|last4=Trncik|first4=Christian|last5=Einsle|first5=Oliver|last6=Keavney|first6=David|last7=DeBeer|first7=Serena|date=2019-07-08|title=X-ray Magnetic Circular Dichroism Spectroscopy Applied to Nitrogenase and Related Models: Experimental Evidence for a Spin-Coupled Molybdenum(III) Center|journal=Angewandte Chemie International Edition|language=en|volume=58|issue=28|pages=9373\u20139377|doi=10.1002/anie.201901899|pmc=6772009|pmid=31119827}}</ref> Another approach in this field concerns comparative studies of different forms of nitrogenase enzymes with FeMoco and FeVco active sites,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Rees|first=Julian A.|last2=Bjornsson|first2=Ragnar|last3=Kowalska|first3=Joanna K.|last4=Lima|first4=Frederico A.|last5=Schlesier|first5=Julia|last6=Sippel|first6=Daniel|last7=Weyherm\u00fcller|first7=Thomas|last8=Einsle|first8=Oliver|last9=Kovacs|first9=Julie A. |authorlink9=Julie Kovacs|last10=DeBeer|first10=Serena|date=2017|title=Comparative electronic structures of nitrogenase FeMoco and FeVco|journal=Dalton Transactions|language=en|volume=46|issue=8|pages=2445\u20132455|doi=10.1039/C7DT00128B|issn=1477-9226|pmc=5322470|pmid=28154874}}</ref> [[Selenium]]-incorporated FeMoco,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Henthorn|first=Justin T.|last2=Arias|first2=Renee J.|last3=Koroidov|first3=Sergey|last4=Kroll|first4=Thomas|last5=Sokaras|first5=Dimosthenis|last6=Bergmann|first6=Uwe|last7=Rees|first7=Douglas C.|last8=DeBeer|first8=Serena|date=2019-08-28|title=Localized Electronic Structure of Nitrogenase FeMoco Revealed by Selenium K-Edge High Resolution X-ray Absorption Spectroscopy|journal=Journal of the American Chemical Society|language=en|volume=141|issue=34|pages=13676\u201313688|doi=10.1021/jacs.9b06988|issn=0002-7863|pmc=6716209|pmid=31356071}}</ref> as well as spectroscopic characterization of the first intermediate state of the nitrogenase catalytic cycle (E<sub>1</sub>).<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Van Stappen|first=Casey|last2=Thorhallsson|first2=Albert Thor|last3=Decamps|first3=Laure|last4=Bjornsson|first4=Ragnar|last5=DeBeer|first5=Serena|date=2019|title=Resolving the structure of the E 1 state of Mo nitrogenase through Mo and Fe K-edge EXAFS and QM/MM calculations|journal=Chemical Science|language=en|volume=10|issue=42|pages=9807\u20139821|doi=10.1039/C9SC02187F|issn=2041-6520}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Van Stappen|first=Casey|last2=Davydov|first2=Roman|last3=Yang|first3=Zhi-Yong|last4=Fan|first4=Ruixi|last5=Guo|first5=Yisong|last6=Bill|first6=Eckhard|last7=Seefeldt|first7=Lance C.|last8=Hoffman|first8=Brian M.|last9=DeBeer|first9=Serena|date=2019-09-16|title=Spectroscopic Description of the E 1 State of Mo Nitrogenase Based on Mo and Fe X-ray Absorption and M\u00f6ssbauer Studies|journal=Inorganic Chemistry|language=en|volume=58|issue=18|pages=12365\u201312376|doi=10.1021/acs.inorgchem.9b01951|issn=0020-1669|pmc=6751781|pmid=31441651}}</ref>\n\n=== Methane monooxygenase ===\nAnother important chemical conversion studied by her group is the catalytic oxidation of [[methane]] to [[methanol]]. Nature utilizes a group of enzymes called [[methane monooxygenase]] (MMOs). The active site of this enzyme that enables the cleavage of the C-H of [[methane]] is a dinuclear Fe(IV) intermediate Q found in the hydroxylase protein (MMOH) of MMO. Spectroscopic studies in the DeBeer group have provided new insights into the structure of this diiron complex. Through applications of advanced X-ray spectroscopic studies like high-resolution [[X-ray absorption spectroscopy|XAS]] they characterized the key intermediate in biological methane oxidation as an open-core diiron structure (with Fe<sup>IV</sup>=O motif).<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Castillo|first=Rebeca G.|last2=Banerjee|first2=Rahul|last3=Allpress|first3=Caleb J.|last4=Rohde|first4=Gregory T.|last5=Bill|first5=Eckhard|last6=Que|first6=Lawrence|last7=Lipscomb|first7=John D.|last8=DeBeer|first8=Serena|date=2017-12-13|title=High-Energy-Resolution Fluorescence-Detected X-ray Absorption of the Q Intermediate of Soluble Methane Monooxygenase|journal=Journal of the American Chemical Society|language=en|volume=139|issue=49|pages=18024\u201318033|doi=10.1021/jacs.7b09560|pmid=29136468|pmc=5729100|issn=0002-7863}}</ref> Additional [[Extended X-ray absorption fine structure|EXAFS]] studies confirmed this finding by showing no evidence for a short Fe-Fe distance but rather a long diiron distance consistent with an open-core structure.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Cutsail|first=George E.|last2=Banerjee|first2=Rahul|last3=Zhou|first3=Ang|last4=Que|first4=Lawrence|last5=Lipscomb|first5=John D.|last6=DeBeer|first6=Serena|date=2018-12-05|title=High-Resolution Extended X-ray Absorption Fine Structure Analysis Provides Evidence for a Longer Fe\u00b7\u00b7\u00b7Fe Distance in the Q Intermediate of Methane Monooxygenase|journal=Journal of the American Chemical Society|language=en|volume=140|issue=48|pages=16807\u201316820|doi=10.1021/jacs.8b10313|pmid=30398343|pmc=6470014|issn=0002-7863}}</ref>\n\n=== Spectroscopy Development ===\nRecent work of DeBeer's group has focused on developing the full information content of various X-ray spectroscopic methods and their application to biological catalysts.\n\nAmong these methods are:\n\n==== Valence X-ray Emission Spectroscopy  ====\nIn this method (also known as VtC XES = Valence-to-Core X-ray Emission Spectroscopy), one monitors the resultant fluorescence after a valence electron refills the ionized metal 1s core hole. As such, valence XES spectra provide a map of ligand ionization energies, and provides information on both ligand identity and protonation state. A prominent application of this method its use to identify the central carbon atom in FeMo cofactor of Nitrogenase  (see section [[Serena DeBeer#Nitrogenase|Nitrogenase]]).<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==== Resonant valence XES (RXES) or Resonant Inelastic X-ray Scattering (RIXS) ====\nThe DeBeer group is actively involved in the development and application of RXES/[[Resonant inelastic X-ray scattering|RIXS]] based methods in both the hard and soft [[X-ray]] regime. These include 1s-Valence [[Resonant inelastic X-ray scattering|RIXS]] as a means to obtain ligand-selective [[X-ray absorption spectroscopy|XAS]]<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Hall|first=Eleanor R.|last2=Pollock|first2=Christopher J.|last3=Bendix|first3=Jesper|last4=Collins|first4=Terrence J.|last5=Glatzel|first5=Pieter|last6=DeBeer|first6=Serena|date=2014-07-16|title=Valence-to-Core-Detected X-ray Absorption Spectroscopy: Targeting Ligand Selectivity|journal=Journal of the American Chemical Society|language=en|volume=136|issue=28|pages=10076\u201310084|doi=10.1021/ja504206y|pmid=24946007|issn=0002-7863}}</ref> and 2p3d [[Resonant inelastic X-ray scattering|RIXS]] as a means to map out the d-d excitations.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Van Kuiken|first=Benjamin E.|last2=Hahn|first2=Anselm W.|last3=Nayyar|first3=Brahamjot|last4=Schiewer|first4=Christine E.|last5=Lee|first5=Sonny C.|last6=Meyer|first6=Franc|last7=Weyherm\u00fcller|first7=Thomas|last8=Nicolaou|first8=Alessandro|last9=Cui|first9=Yi-Tao|last10=Miyawaki|first10=Jun|last11=Harada|first11=Yoshihisa|date=2018-06-18|title=Electronic Spectra of Iron\u2013Sulfur Complexes Measured by 2p3d RIXS Spectroscopy|journal=Inorganic Chemistry|language=en|volume=57|issue=12|pages=7355\u20137361|doi=10.1021/acs.inorgchem.8b01010|pmid=29847108|issn=0020-1669}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Hahn|first=Anselm W.|last2=Van Kuiken|first2=Benjamin E.|last3=al Samarai|first3=Mustafa|last4=Atanasov|first4=Mihail|last5=Weyherm\u00fcller|first5=Thomas|last6=Cui|first6=Yi-Tao|last7=Miyawaki|first7=Jun|last8=Harada|first8=Yoshihisa|last9=Nicolaou|first9=Alessandro|last10=DeBeer|first10=Serena|date=2017-07-17|title=Measurement of the Ligand Field Spectra of Ferrous and Ferric Iron Chlorides Using 2p3d RIXS|journal=Inorganic Chemistry|language=en|volume=56|issue=14|pages=8203\u20138211|doi=10.1021/acs.inorgchem.7b00940|pmid=28653856|issn=0020-1669}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Hahn|first=Anselm W.|last2=Van Kuiken|first2=Benjamin E.|last3=Chilkuri|first3=Vijay Gopal|last4=Levin|first4=Natalia|last5=Bill|first5=Eckhard|last6=Weyherm\u00fcller|first6=Thomas|last7=Nicolaou|first7=Alessandro|last8=Miyawaki|first8=Jun|last9=Harada|first9=Yoshihisa|last10=DeBeer|first10=Serena|date=2018-08-06|title=Probing the Valence Electronic Structure of Low-Spin Ferrous and Ferric Complexes Using 2p3d Resonant Inelastic X-ray Scattering (RIXS)|journal=Inorganic Chemistry|language=en|volume=57|issue=15|pages=9515\u20139530|doi=10.1021/acs.inorgchem.8b01550|pmid=30044087|issn=0020-1669}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Van Kuiken|first=Benjamin E.|last2=Hahn|first2=Anselm W.|last3=Maganas|first3=Dimitrios|last4=DeBeer|first4=Serena|date=2016-11-07|title=Measuring Spin-Allowed and Spin-Forbidden d\u2013d Excitations in Vanadium Complexes with 2p3d Resonant Inelastic X-ray Scattering|journal=Inorganic Chemistry|language=en|volume=55|issue=21|pages=11497\u201311501|doi=10.1021/acs.inorgchem.6b02053|pmid=27731986|issn=0020-1669}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Maganas|first=Dimitrios|last2=DeBeer|first2=Serena|last3=Neese|first3=Frank|date=2017-10-02|title=A Restricted Open Configuration Interaction with Singles Method To Calculate Valence-to-Core Resonant X-ray Emission Spectra: A Case Study|journal=Inorganic Chemistry|language=en|volume=56|issue=19|pages=11819\u201311836|doi=10.1021/acs.inorgchem.7b01810|issn=0020-1669|pmc=5692824|pmid=28920680}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Al Samarai|first=Mustafa|last2=Hahn|first2=Anselm W.|last3=Beheshti Askari|first3=Abbas|last4=Cui|first4=Yi-Tao|last5=Yamazoe|first5=Kosuke|last6=Miyawaki|first6=Jun|last7=Harada|first7=Yoshihisa|last8=R\u00fcdiger|first8=Olaf|last9=DeBeer|first9=Serena|date=2019-10-23|title=Elucidation of Structure\u2013Activity Correlations in a Nickel Manganese Oxide Oxygen Evolution Reaction Catalyst by Operando Ni L-Edge X-ray Absorption Spectroscopy and 2p3d Resonant Inelastic X-ray Scattering|journal=ACS Applied Materials & Interfaces|language=en|volume=11|issue=42|pages=38595\u201338605|doi=10.1021/acsami.9b06752|pmid=31523947|issn=1944-8244}}</ref>\n\n==== X-ray Magnetic Circular Dichroism (XMCD) ====\nThis method has been extensively used in solid-state materials, to determine the magnetic properties. Past applications to (bio-)inorganic or protein systems were lacking proper qualitative and quantitative interpretations. DeBeer's group expanded the information that can be obtained from XMCD of covalent systems.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kowalska|first=Joanna K.|last2=Nayyar|first2=Brahamjot|last3=Rees|first3=Julian A.|last4=Schiewer|first4=Christine E.|last5=Lee|first5=Sonny C.|last6=Kovacs|first6=Julie A.|last7=Meyer|first7=Franc|last8=Weyherm\u00fcller|first8=Thomas|last9=Otero|first9=Edwige|last10=DeBeer|first10=Serena|date=2017-07-17|title=Iron L 2,3 -Edge X-ray Absorption and X-ray Magnetic Circular Dichroism Studies of Molecular Iron Complexes with Relevance to the FeMoco and FeVco Active Sites of Nitrogenase|journal=Inorganic Chemistry|language=en|volume=56|issue=14|pages=8147\u20138158|doi=10.1021/acs.inorgchem.7b00852|issn=0020-1669|pmc=5516708|pmid=28653855}}</ref> To date, this been the only one method able to provide evidence for the proposed non-Hund configuration at the Mo atom in Nitrogenase<ref name=\":1\" /> (see section [[Serena DeBeer#Nitrogenase|Nitrogeanse]]).\n\n=== Instrumentation ===\n\n==== A laboratory based dispersive X-ray Emission Spectrometer ====\nThe group of Serena DeBeer in collaboration with the group of Prof. Birgit Kangie\u00dfer at [[Technical University of Berlin|TU Berlin]], developed an in-house dispersive X-ray Emission Spectroscopy (XES) setup. The setup that utilizes a laboratory X\u2011ray source (Metal Jet) in combination with a von Hamos full cylinder optic with Highly Annealed Pyrolytic Graphite (HAPG) crystal and a CCD detector. This allows obtaining spectra in the 2.4-9 keV range. Moreover, this spectrometer is an alternative to synchrotron-based beamlines for concentrated samples.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Malzer|first=Wolfgang|last2=Gr\u00f6tzsch|first2=Daniel|last3=Gnewkow|first3=Richard|last4=Schlesiger|first4=Christopher|last5=Kowalewski|first5=Fabian|last6=Van Kuiken|first6=Benjamin|last7=DeBeer|first7=Serena|last8=Kanngie\u00dfer|first8=Birgit|date=November 2018|title=A laboratory spectrometer for high throughput X-ray emission spectroscopy in catalysis research|journal=Review of Scientific Instruments|language=en|volume=89|issue=11|pages=113111|doi=10.1063/1.5035171|pmid=30501328|issn=0034-6748|bibcode=2018RScI...89k3111M}}</ref>\n\n==== PINK Beamline ====\nThe DeBeer group is also leading the development of the PINK beamline<ref name=\":2\" /> at the Energy Materials In-situ Laboratory<ref name=\":3\" /> at the [[Helmholtz-Zentrum Berlin|Helmholtz Zentrum Berlin]]. Dr. Sergey Peredkov is the lead designer and instrument scientist for this project. This beamline operates in 2-10 keV energy regime, either in a \u201cpink\u201d beam mode with multilayer mirror or with monochromatic beam (by addition of a double crystal [[monochromator]]). The beamline is presently in a commissioning phase.\n\n== Awards and recognition ==\n\n* [[European Research Council]] (ERC) Synergy Grant for the project: Unravelling the secrets of Cu-based catalysts for C-H activation (CUBE). Collaborative project with researchers from [[University of Oslo]] (Norway), [[Norwegian University of Life Sciences]] (Norway) and [[University of Turin]] (Italy) (2019) <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cec.mpg.de/en/news/detail-view/news/erc-synergy-grant-for-serena-debeer-and-an-international-and-interdisciplinary-team/|title=ERC Synergy Grant for Serena DeBeer and an international and interdisciplinary team|website=cec.mpg.de|access-date=2019-11-27}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://erc.europa.eu/news-events/magazine/erc-2019-synergy-grants-examples|title=ERC 2019 Synergy Grants examples|date=2019-10-10|website=ERC: European Research Council|language=en|access-date=2019-11-27}}</ref>\n* Associate Editor for [[Chemical Science (journal)|Chemical Science]] (2018\u2013present)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blogs.rsc.org/sc/2018/12/11/serena-debeer-joins-chemical-science/|title=Serena DeBeer joins Chemical Science as an Associate Editor \u2013 Chemical Science Blog|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-27}}</ref>\n* Inorganic Chemistry Lectureship Award (2016) <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://communities.acs.org/groups/wcc-newsletter/blog/2017/06/06/dr-serena-debeer-2016-inorganic-chemistry-lecturship-award|title=Dr. Serena Debeer - 2016 Inorganic Chemistry Le... {{!}} ACS Network|website=communities.acs.org|access-date=2019-11-27}}</ref>\n* [[Society of Biological Inorganic Chemistry]] (SBIC), Early Career Award (2015)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://sbichem.org/SBIC-News/2015-SBIC-Early-Career-Award-Winner-Serena-DeBeer.aspx|title=Serena DeBeer SBIC Early Career Award|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n* [[European Research Council|European Research Counc]][[European Research Council|il]] (ERC) Consolidator grant for the project: Spectroscopic Studies of N<sub>2</sub> Reduction: From Biological to Heterogeneous Catalysis (N2ase) (2013)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cordis.europa.eu/project/rcn/191266/factsheet/it|title=ERC Consolidator Grant: N2ase|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n* Kavli Fellow, [[National Academy of Sciences|U.S. National Academy of Sciences]] (2012)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nasonline.org/programs/kavli-frontiers-of-science/frontiers-alumni/alumni-directory/serena-debeer.html|title=Serena DeBeer|website=www.nasonline.org|access-date=2019-11-27}}</ref>\n* [[Sloan Research Fellowship|Alfred P. Sloan Research Fellow]] (2011-2013)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sloan.org/past-fellows|title=Past Fellows|website=sloan.org|access-date=2019-11-27}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://cec.mpg.de/1/research/1087/prof-dr-serena-debeer/ Prof. Dr. Ser][https://cec.mpg.de/1/research/1087/prof-dr-serena-debeer/ ena DeBeer]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:DeBeer, Serena}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American women chemists]]\n[[Category:Stanford University alumni]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women scientists]]\n[[Category:Cornell University faculty]]\n[[Category:1973 births]]\n", "name_user": "JKowalska", "label": "safe", "comment": "link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Serena_DeBeer"}
{"title_page": "Lugoj", "text_new": "{{Infobox Romanian subdivision\n|type                   = municipality\n|county                 = Timi\u0219\n|population_total       = auto\n|map_caption            = Location in Timi\u0219 County\n|official_name                     =Lugoj\n|other_name                        = {{lang|hu|Lugos}}<br/>{{lang|de|Lugosch}}\n|image_skyline                     =Lugojchurch.jpg\n|image_caption                     =Baroque Orthodox Cathedral         \n|image_shield                      =ROU TM Lugoj CoA.jpg\n|image_map              = Lugoj jud Timis.png\n|leader_name                       =Francisc Boldea<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.2016bec.ro/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/SIAL2016_P_Lista_Moc-2.xlsx |title=Results of the 2016 local elections |publisher=Central Electoral Bureau |accessdate=2020-04-03 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n|leader_party                      =PSD\n|area_total_km2                    =88.05\n|coordinates                       = {{coord|45|41|10|N|21|54|2|E|region:RO|display=inline,title}}\n|website                           ={{url|http://www.primarialugoj.ro/}}\n}}\n\n[[File:Lugoj1.jpg|thumb|View from a bridge in Lugoj]]\n\n'''Lugoj''' ({{IPA-ro|\u02c8lu\u0261o\u0292}}) is a [[municipiu|city]] in [[Timi\u0219 County]], [[Banat]], western [[Romania]]. The river [[Timi\u0219 (river)|Timi\u0219]] divides the city into two halves, the so-called Romanian Lugoj that spreads on the right bank and the [[Banat Swabians|German]] Lugoj on the left bank. The city administers two villages, M\u0103guri ({{lang-hu|Szendelak}}) and Tapia ({{lang-hu|T\u00e1pia}}).\n\n==Etymology==\nIn {{lang-de|Lugosch}}; in {{lang-sr|Lugo\u0161}} (\u041b\u0443\u0433\u043e\u0448); in {{lang-hu|Lugos}}; in {{lang-tr|Logo\u015f}}.\n\n==History==\n[[File:Lugoj 1804.jpg|thumb|right|Queen Mary Market (Pia\u021ba Regina Maria) area in 1804]]\n[[File:Th\u00e9odore Valerio, Paysans valaques des environs de Lugos, Romanian peasants from around Lugos, 1851.jpg|thumb|right|{{ill|Th\u00e9odore Valerio|fr}}, Romanian peasants from around Lugos, 1851]]\n\nLugoj was once a strongly fortified city that developed along the river [[Timi\u0219 (river)|Timi\u0219]]. During the Middle Ages and eighteenth century, it was of greater relative importance than at present.\n\nA diploma dated Wednesday 22 August 1376, signed by King [[Sigismund of Luxemburg]], shows that Lugoj city was donated to Losonczy family. At the end of the 14th century, after the [[Battle of Nicopolis]] (1396), the Turks crossed the Danube, invading the region of Banat and reached the gates of Lugoj. The city was strengthened with trenches, ramparts and palisades in 1440 by the initiatives of Hunyadi, as a comite of Timis , in order to its defense system. It resisted Ottoman pressures until 1658, when the Prince of Transylvania asked Lugoj and [[Caransebe\u0219]] to accept the decision taken by the Diet of Sighi\u0219oara to agree to Turkish occupation.\n\nAfter the defeat of the Turks during the [[Battle of Vienna]] in 1683, the Habsburgs went on the offensive and briefly occupied the cities of Lugoj and Lipova (1688). On September 25, 1695 the battle between the armies of the [[Habsburg Monarchy]] and the [[Ottoman Empire]] that took place near Lugoj ended with the defeat of the Austrians.\n\nAfter signing the [[Treaty of Karlovitz]] (1699), the region of Banat remained under Ottoman rule for nearly 20 years. The [[Treaty of Passarowitz]] (21 July 1718) was signed and the Turks were expelled. The Habsburg Monarchy wanted to repopulate the Banat, which had emptied following the years of occupation and earlier [[bubonic plague]]. The government recruited Germans from [[Bavaria]], [[Swabia]] and Alsace-Lorraine, particularly farmers to revive agriculture in the rich floodplain. They traveled down the Danube River on boats to this area.  They later took the rafts apart to use to build their first houses. In this area, the first German colonists settled on the left bank of the river [[Timi\u0219 (river)|Timi\u0219]] (circa 1720), creating what was called \"German Lugoj\". The government had offered them the privileges of keeping their German language and religion; most were Roman Catholic.\n\nIn the 18th century, many public buildings were built in the city, including the Roman Catholic Church and the Orthodox Church \"Assumption\". In 1778, following the incorporation of [[Banat]] into Hungary, Lugoj became the county seat of Cara\u0219. In 1795 the government unified the Romanian Lugoj and the German Lugoj.\n\n[[Eftimie Murgu]] settled in Lugoj in 1841.  In June 1848 he chaired the second [[National Assembly]] of Romanians of Banat, where they expressed in postulates the National Order of Romanians during the Revolutionary Movement from Banat, whose center was Lugoj.\n\nIn the summer of 1842 a great fire took place, in which about 400 houses and important buildings were destroyed.\n\nIn August 1849 Lugoj was the last seat of the [[Hungarian Revolution of 1848|Hungarian revolutionary government]]. It served as the last refuge of [[Lajos Kossuth]] and several other leaders of the Revolution prior to their escape to the [[Ottoman Empire]].\n\nUnder the imperial resolution of 12 December 1850, Lugoj became the seat of the Greek-Catholic Diocese of Banat. Lugoj was the seat of [[Krass\u00f3-Sz\u00f6r\u00e9ny County]] from 1881 to 1918. Following the break-up of Austria-Hungary at the end of World War I, the region of Banat, after a brief period of Serbian occupation came under Romanian administration. [[Severin County]] was organized and named, and its seat was located in Lugoj until the temporary abolition of counties in 1950.\n\nThe Iron Bridge, a symbol of Lugoj, was built in 1902. On November 3, 1918 a Great National Assembly took place in Lugoj. The right of self-determination of the Romanian nation was proclaimed after the dissolution of the [[Austro-Hungarian Empire]] in World War I.\n\nIn modern times, the city was the home town of famous Dracula actor [[Bela Lugosi]].\n\nIt is the seat of the [[Eparchy of Lugoj]] in the [[Romanian Church United with Rome, Greek-Catholic]].\n\n==Population and demographics==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:93%;width:300px;height:16;border:0px;text-align:left;line-height:120%; margin-bottom: 10px\"\n|-\n| colspan=\"14\" style=\"text-align:center; background: #F4F4F4\" height=24px |'''Historical population of Lugoj'''<ref>[http://varga.adatbank.transindex.ro/?pg=3&action=etnik&id=3608 Erd\u00e9ly etnikai \u00e9s felekezeti statisztik\u00e1ja<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n|-\n! Year\n! Population\n! Romanians\n! Hungarians\n! Germans\n|-\n| 1880\n| 12,389\n| 46.8%\n| 11.6%\n| 36.9%\n|-\n| 1890\n| 13,548\n| 46%\n| 13.8%\n| 38.3%\n|- \n| 1900\n| 17,486\n| 37.9%\n| 22.7%\n| 35.9%\n|- \n| 1910\n| 20,962 \n| 34.9%\n| 32.9%\n| 29.5%\n|- \n| 1920\n| 21,172\n| 41.2%\n| 20.1%\n| 28.3%\n|- \n| 1930\n| 24,694 \n| 43.3%\n| 21.9%\n| 24.9%\n|-\n| 1941\n| 27,871\n| 51.6%\n| 17%\n| 21.7%\n|-\n| 1956\n| 31,364 \n| 63.4%\n| 17.8%\n| 13.6%\n|- \n| 1966\n| 36,728 \n| 68%\n| 16.3%\n| 12.4%\n|- \n| 1977\n| 44,537  \n| 72.6%\n| 13.8%\n| 10.7%\n|- \n| 1992\n| 50,939 \n| 79.8%\n| 10.7%\n| 5.2%\n|- \n| 2002\n| 44,636\n| 83%\n| 9.6%\n| 3%\n|- \n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n| colspan=\"14\" style=\"text-align:center; background: #F4F4F4\" height=24px |'''Detailed Demographics \u2013 2011'''\n|-\n! Ethnic group\n! Number\n! Percentage\n|-\n| [[Romanians]]\n| 32,036\n| 85.83%\n|-\n| [[Hungarian minority in Romania|Hungarians]]\n| 2,727\n| 7.3%\n|-\n| [[Germans of Romania|Germans]]\n| 744\n| 1.99%\n|-\n| [[Roma minority in Romania|Roma]]\n| 905\n| 2.42%\n|-\n| [[Ukrainians of Romania|Ukrainians]]\n| 508\n| 1.36%\n|-\n| Other\n| 398\n| 0.6%\n|-\n| '''Total'''\n| '''37,321'''\n| '''100%'''\n|}\n\n==Senior High and Post-secondary Education==\n[[File:Lugos 1889 Roumanie.jpg|thumb|left|150px|Lugos cancellation in 1889, Kingdom of Hungary]]\n*Coriolan Brediceanu National College\n*Iulia Ha\u0219deu National College\n*Aurel Vlaicu School Group\n*Valeriu Brani\u0219te College\n*[[Dr\u0103gan European University of Lugoj]]\n\n{{clr}}\n\n==Natives==\n*[[Simona Arghir]], handballer\n*[[Filaret Barbu]], operetta composer\n*[[Gelu Barbu]], ballet dancer and choreographer\n*[[Caius Brediceanu]], diplomat\n*[[Coriolan Brediceanu]], politician  and lawyer\n*[[Tiberiu Brediceanu]], composer\n*[[Corina Caprioriu]], judoka\n*[[Aurel Ciupe]], painter\n*[[Konstantin Danil]], portraiture painter\n*[[Georges Devereux]], ethnopsychologist\n*[[Iosif Constantin Dr\u0103gan]], businessman and author\n*[[Traian Groz\u0103vescu]], opera tenor\n*[[Sepp Helfrich]], Austrian National Socialist\n*[[August Kanitz]], botanist \n*[[Gy\u00f6rgy Kurt\u00e1g]], composer\n*[[Bela Lugosi]], actor\n*[[Lavinia Milo\u0219ovici]], gymnast\n*[[Victor Neumann]], historian\n*[[Dumitru P\u00e2rvulescu]], wrestler\n*[[Aurel Popovici]], politician\n*[[Ioan Popovici-B\u0103n\u0103\u021beanul]], writer and poet\n*[[Josef Posipal]], soccer player\n*[[Michael Redl]], handball player and coach\n*[[Otilia Ruicu-E\u0219anu]], 400m athlete\n*[[B\u00e9la Szende]], politician\n*[[Aura Twarowska]], mezzo-soprano\n*[[Koloman Wallisch]], labor leader\n\n==International relations==\n{{See also|List of twin towns and sister cities in Romania}}\n\n===Twin towns \u2014 Sister cities===\nLugoj is [[Twin towns and sister cities|twinned]] with:\n*{{flagicon|SRB}} [[Vr\u0161ac]]\n*{{flagicon|HUN}} [[Szeksz\u00e1rd]]\n*{{flagicon|FRA}} [[Orl\u00e9ans]]\n*{{flagicon|GER}} [[Jena]]\n*{{flagicon|GRE}} [[Assos-Lechaio]]\n*{{flagicon|MDA}} [[Nisporeni]]\n*{{flagicon|ITA}} [[Monopoli]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Lugoj}}\n{{wikivoyage|Lugoj}}\n* [http://www.primarialugoj.ro/ City Hall site]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120419184613/http://www.lugojul.ro/ Lugojul \u2013 local info site]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060903015428/http://www.lugoj.ro/index.htm Lugoj]\n* [http://www.lugoj-live.ro/ Lugoj fun]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20140808201137/http://www.universitateaeuropeanadragan.ro/ \"Dr\u0103gan\" European University of Lugoj]\n* [http://www.ziarulactualitatea.ro Actualitatea, weekly newspaper]\n* [http://www.redesteptarea.ro/ Rede\u015fteptarea, weekly newspaper]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20160305110649/http://www.lugojonline.ro.ro/ Lugoj Online, online newspaper]\n\n{{Timi\u0219 County}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Lugoj| ]]\n[[Category:Cities in Romania]]\n[[Category:Populated places in Timi\u0219 County]]\n[[Category:Capitals of former Romanian counties]]\n[[Category:Localities in Romanian Banat]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Romanian subdivision\n|type                   = municipality\n|county                 = Timi\u0219\n|population_total       = auto\n|map_caption            = Location in Timi\u0219 County\n|official_name                     =Lugoj\n|other_name                        = {{lang|hu|Lugos}}<br/>{{lang|de|Lugosch}}\n|image_skyline                     =Lugojchurch.jpg\n|image_caption                     =Baroque Orthodox Cathedral         \n|image_shield                      =ROU TM Lugoj CoA.jpg\n|image_map              = Lugoj jud Timis.png\n|leader_name                       =Francisc Boldea\n|leader_party                      =PSD\n|area_total_km2                    =88.05\n|coordinates                       = {{coord|45|41|10|N|21|54|2|E|region:RO|display=inline,title}}\n|website                           ={{url|http://www.primarialugoj.ro/}}\n}}\n\n[[File:Lugoj1.jpg|thumb|View from a bridge in Lugoj]]\n\n'''Lugoj''' ({{IPA-ro|\u02c8lu\u0261o\u0292}}) is a [[municipiu|city]] in [[Timi\u0219 County]], [[Banat]], western [[Romania]]. The river [[Timi\u0219 (river)|Timi\u0219]] divides the city into two halves, the so-called Romanian Lugoj that spreads on the right bank and the [[Banat Swabians|German]] Lugoj on the left bank. The city administers two villages, M\u0103guri ({{lang-hu|Szendelak}}) and Tapia ({{lang-hu|T\u00e1pia}}).\n\n==Etymology==\nIn {{lang-de|Lugosch}}; in {{lang-sr|Lugo\u0161}} (\u041b\u0443\u0433\u043e\u0448); in {{lang-hu|Lugos}}; in {{lang-tr|Logo\u015f}}.\n\n==History==\n[[File:Lugoj 1804.jpg|thumb|right|Queen Mary Market (Pia\u021ba Regina Maria) area in 1804]]\n[[File:Th\u00e9odore Valerio, Paysans valaques des environs de Lugos, Romanian peasants from around Lugos, 1851.jpg|thumb|right|{{ill|Th\u00e9odore Valerio|fr}}, Romanian peasants from around Lugos, 1851]]\n\nLugoj was once a strongly fortified city that developed along the river [[Timi\u0219 (river)|Timi\u0219]]. During the Middle Ages and eighteenth century, it was of greater relative importance than at present.\n\nA diploma dated Wednesday 22 August 1376, signed by King [[Sigismund of Luxemburg]], shows that Lugoj city was donated to Losonczy family. At the end of the 14th century, after the [[Battle of Nicopolis]] (1396), the Turks crossed the Danube, invading the region of Banat and reached the gates of Lugoj. The city was strengthened with trenches, ramparts and palisades in 1440 by the initiatives of Hunyadi, as a comite of Timis , in order to its defense system. It resisted Ottoman pressures until 1658, when the Prince of Transylvania asked Lugoj and [[Caransebe\u0219]] to accept the decision taken by the Diet of Sighi\u0219oara to agree to Turkish occupation.\n\nAfter the defeat of the Turks during the [[Battle of Vienna]] in 1683, the Habsburgs went on the offensive and briefly occupied the cities of Lugoj and Lipova (1688). On September 25, 1695 the battle between the armies of the [[Habsburg Monarchy]] and the [[Ottoman Empire]] that took place near Lugoj ended with the defeat of the Austrians.\n\nAfter signing the [[Treaty of Karlovitz]] (1699), the region of Banat remained under Ottoman rule for nearly 20 years. The [[Treaty of Passarowitz]] (21 July 1718) was signed and the Turks were expelled. The Habsburg Monarchy wanted to repopulate the Banat, which had emptied following the years of occupation and earlier [[bubonic plague]]. The government recruited Germans from [[Bavaria]], [[Swabia]] and Alsace-Lorraine, particularly farmers to revive agriculture in the rich floodplain. They traveled down the Danube River on boats to this area.  They later took the rafts apart to use to build their first houses. In this area, the first German colonists settled on the left bank of the river [[Timi\u0219 (river)|Timi\u0219]] (circa 1720), creating what was called \"German Lugoj\". The government had offered them the privileges of keeping their German language and religion; most were Roman Catholic.\n\nIn the 18th century, many public buildings were built in the city, including the Roman Catholic Church and the Orthodox Church \"Assumption\". In 1778, following the incorporation of [[Banat]] into Hungary, Lugoj became the county seat of Cara\u0219. In 1795 the government unified the Romanian Lugoj and the German Lugoj.\n\n[[Eftimie Murgu]] settled in Lugoj in 1841.  In June 1848 he chaired the second [[National Assembly]] of Romanians of Banat, where they expressed in postulates the National Order of Romanians during the Revolutionary Movement from Banat, whose center was Lugoj.\n\nIn the summer of 1842 a great fire took place, in which about 400 houses and important buildings were destroyed.\n\nIn August 1849 Lugoj was the last seat of the [[Hungarian Revolution of 1848|Hungarian revolutionary government]]. It served as the last refuge of [[Lajos Kossuth]] and several other leaders of the Revolution prior to their escape to the [[Ottoman Empire]].\n\nUnder the imperial resolution of 12 December 1850, Lugoj became the seat of the Greek-Catholic Diocese of Banat. Lugoj was the seat of [[Krass\u00f3-Sz\u00f6r\u00e9ny County]] from 1881 to 1918. Following the break-up of Austria-Hungary at the end of World War I, the region of Banat, after a brief period of Serbian occupation came under Romanian administration. [[Severin County]] was organized and named, and its seat was located in Lugoj until the temporary abolition of counties in 1950.\n\nThe Iron Bridge, a symbol of Lugoj, was built in 1902. On November 3, 1918 a Great National Assembly took place in Lugoj. The right of self-determination of the Romanian nation was proclaimed after the dissolution of the [[Austro-Hungarian Empire]] in World War I.\n\nIn modern times, the city was the home town of famous Dracula actor [[Bela Lugosi]].\n\nIt is the seat of the [[Eparchy of Lugoj]] in the [[Romanian Church United with Rome, Greek-Catholic]].\n\n==Population and demographics==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:93%;width:300px;height:16;border:0px;text-align:left;line-height:120%; margin-bottom: 10px\"\n|-\n| colspan=\"14\" style=\"text-align:center; background: #F4F4F4\" height=24px |'''Historical population of Lugoj'''<ref>[http://varga.adatbank.transindex.ro/?pg=3&action=etnik&id=3608 Erd\u00e9ly etnikai \u00e9s felekezeti statisztik\u00e1ja<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n|-\n! Year\n! Population\n! Romanians\n! Hungarians\n! Germans\n|-\n| 1880\n| 12,389\n| 46.8%\n| 11.6%\n| 36.9%\n|-\n| 1890\n| 13,548\n| 46%\n| 13.8%\n| 38.3%\n|- \n| 1900\n| 17,486\n| 37.9%\n| 22.7%\n| 35.9%\n|- \n| 1910\n| 20,962 \n| 34.9%\n| 32.9%\n| 29.5%\n|- \n| 1920\n| 21,172\n| 41.2%\n| 20.1%\n| 28.3%\n|- \n| 1930\n| 24,694 \n| 43.3%\n| 21.9%\n| 24.9%\n|-\n| 1941\n| 27,871\n| 51.6%\n| 17%\n| 21.7%\n|-\n| 1956\n| 31,364 \n| 63.4%\n| 17.8%\n| 13.6%\n|- \n| 1966\n| 36,728 \n| 68%\n| 16.3%\n| 12.4%\n|- \n| 1977\n| 44,537  \n| 72.6%\n| 13.8%\n| 10.7%\n|- \n| 1992\n| 50,939 \n| 79.8%\n| 10.7%\n| 5.2%\n|- \n| 2002\n| 44,636\n| 83%\n| 9.6%\n| 3%\n|- \n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n| colspan=\"14\" style=\"text-align:center; background: #F4F4F4\" height=24px |'''Detailed Demographics \u2013 2011'''\n|-\n! Ethnic group\n! Number\n! Percentage\n|-\n| [[Romanians]]\n| 32,036\n| 85.83%\n|-\n| [[Hungarian minority in Romania|Hungarians]]\n| 2,727\n| 7.3%\n|-\n| [[Germans of Romania|Germans]]\n| 744\n| 1.99%\n|-\n| [[Roma minority in Romania|Roma]]\n| 905\n| 2.42%\n|-\n| [[Ukrainians of Romania|Ukrainians]]\n| 508\n| 1.36%\n|-\n| Other\n| 398\n| 0.6%\n|-\n| '''Total'''\n| '''37,321'''\n| '''100%'''\n|}\n\n==Senior High and Post-secondary Education==\n[[File:Lugos 1889 Roumanie.jpg|thumb|left|150px|Lugos cancellation in 1889, Kingdom of Hungary]]\n*Coriolan Brediceanu National College\n*Iulia Ha\u0219deu National College\n*Aurel Vlaicu School Group\n*Valeriu Brani\u0219te College\n*[[Dr\u0103gan European University of Lugoj]]\n\n{{clr}}\n\n==Natives==\n*[[Simona Arghir]], handballer\n*[[Filaret Barbu]], operetta composer\n*[[Gelu Barbu]], ballet dancer and choreographer\n*[[Caius Brediceanu]], diplomat\n*[[Coriolan Brediceanu]], politician  and lawyer\n*[[Tiberiu Brediceanu]], composer\n*[[Corina Caprioriu]], judoka\n*[[Aurel Ciupe]], painter\n*[[Konstantin Danil]], portraiture painter\n*[[Georges Devereux]], ethnopsychologist\n*[[Iosif Constantin Dr\u0103gan]], businessman and author\n*[[Traian Groz\u0103vescu]], opera tenor\n*[[Sepp Helfrich]], Austrian National Socialist\n*[[August Kanitz]], botanist \n*[[Gy\u00f6rgy Kurt\u00e1g]], composer\n*[[Bela Lugosi]], actor\n*[[Lavinia Milo\u0219ovici]], gymnast\n*[[Victor Neumann]], historian\n*[[Dumitru P\u00e2rvulescu]], wrestler\n*[[Aurel Popovici]], politician\n*[[Ioan Popovici-B\u0103n\u0103\u021beanul]], writer and poet\n*[[Josef Posipal]], soccer player\n*[[Michael Redl]], handball player and coach\n*[[Otilia Ruicu-E\u0219anu]], 400m athlete\n*[[B\u00e9la Szende]], politician\n*[[Aura Twarowska]], mezzo-soprano\n*[[Koloman Wallisch]], labor leader\n\n==International relations==\n{{See also|List of twin towns and sister cities in Romania}}\n\n===Twin towns \u2014 Sister cities===\nLugoj is [[Twin towns and sister cities|twinned]] with:\n*{{flagicon|SRB}} [[Vr\u0161ac]]\n*{{flagicon|HUN}} [[Szeksz\u00e1rd]]\n*{{flagicon|FRA}} [[Orl\u00e9ans]]\n*{{flagicon